<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="s_ring_integers" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Quadratic rings of integers</title>

    <subsection xml:id="ss_quadratic_ext">
    <title>Quadratic extensions of <m>\Q</m></title>
    <definition xml:id="d_">
    <title>Quadratic extension of <m>\Q</m></title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Let <m>d\in \Z-\{0,1\}</m> be a squarefree integer. We define <m>\Q(\sqrt{d})</m> to be the following subset of <m>\C</m>: 
    <md number="yes">
        <mrow>\Q(\sqrt{d}) \amp = \{z\in \C\mid z=q_1+q_2\sqrt{d} \text{ for some } q_1,q_2\in \Q\}</mrow>
    </md>.
    We call <m>\Q(\sqrt{d})</m> a <term>quadratic field extension</term> of <m>\Q</m>, or a <term>quadratic subfield</term> of <m>\C</m>. 
    </p>
    <p>
        The quadratic field <m>\Q(\sqrt{d})</m> is <term>real</term> if <m>\Q(\sqrt{d})\subseteq \R</m> (<ie/>, if <m>d\geq 0</m>) and <term>imaginary</term> otherwise (<ie/>, if <m>d&lt; 0</m>).
    </p>
    </statement>
    </definition>
    <remark>
    <title>Quadratic field extensions</title>
    <p>
    You will likely notice the similarity in notation between quadratic fields <m>\Q(\sqrt{d})</m> and the Gaussian integers <m>\Z[i]</m>. Notice further some important differences: the <m>\Q</m> in the first notation is an indication that the set consists of <m>Q</m>-linear combinations <m>q_1+q_2\sqrt{d}</m>, <m>q_1,q_2\in \Q</m> as opposed to <m>\Z</m>-linear combinations <m>a+b\sqrt{d}</m>, <m>a,b\in \Z</m>. Moreover, the use of parentheses in <m>\Q(\sqrt{d})</m> as opposed to brackets (as in <m>\Z[i]</m>) is a notational indication that <m>\Q(\sqrt{d})</m> is a <em>field</em> and not just a ring. (See <xref ref="th_quad_ext_field"/>.)
    </p>
    <p>
        The quadratic fields <m>K=\Q(\sqrt{d})</m> can be thought of as generalizations of <m>\Q</m>. The analog of <m>\Z</m> in these settings is given by the <em>ring of integers</em> <m>\mathcal{O}_K</m> defined below. 
    </p>
    </remark>
    <p>
    You might be wondering about the importance of this squarefree condition. This will arise at various points in our discussion. Our first example is the simple characterization of equality in <m>\Q(\sqrt{d})</m> given below. 
    </p>
    <proposition xml:id="prop_quad_ext_equality">
        <title>Equality in <m>\Q(\sqrt{d})</m></title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>d\in \Z-\{0,1\}</m> be a squarefree integer, and let <m>K=\Q(\sqrt{d})</m>.
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            For all nonzero <m>q\in \Q</m>, <m>q^2d</m> is not a square in <m>\Q</m>. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            We have 
                            <md>
                            <mrow>q_1+q_2\sqrt{d}=q_1'+q_2'\sqrt{d} \amp \iff q_1=q_1' \text{ and } q_2=q_2'</mrow>
                                </md>
                        for all <m>\alpha=q_1+q_2\sqrt{d}</m> and <m>\beta=q_1'+q_2'\sqrt{d}</m> in <m>K</m>. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            If <m>d</m> is negative, then clearly <m>q^2d</m> is negative, and hence not a square in <m>\Q</m>. Assume <m>d&gt; 1</m>. If <m>q^2d=r^2</m> for some <m>r\in \Q</m>, then after expressing <m>q</m> and <m>r</m> as quotients of integers and clearing denominators, we see that we have <m>n^2d=m^2</m> for some nonzero integers <m>n</m> and <m>m</m>. Let <m>p</m> be any prime divisor of <m>d</m>. Since it appears with exponent <m>1</m> in the prime factorization of <m>d</m> (<m>d</m> is squarefree), it appears with odd exponent in the prime factorization of <m>n^2d</m>. But this contradicts the fact that <m>n^2d=m^2</m>. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The reverse implication is obvious. For the forward implication, we have 
    <md number="yes">
        <mrow>q_1+q_2\sqrt{d}=q_1'+q_2'\sqrt{d} \amp \implies (q_1-q_1')+(q_2-q_2')\sqrt{d}=0 </mrow>
    </md>.
    If <m>q_2-q_2'\ne 0</m>, we would have <m>\sqrt{d}\in \Q</m>. But this is impossible: if <m>d=(m/n)^2</m>, then we would have <m>n^2d=m^2</m>, contradicting (1). Thus we must have <m>q_2-q_2'=0</m>, or equivalently <m>q_2=q_2'</m>. It then follows tautologically that <m>q_1=q_1'</m>. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </proof>
    </proposition>
    <definition xml:id="d_quad_conjugate_norm">
    <title>Quadratic norm and conjugate</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Let <m>d\in \Z-\{0,1\}</m> be squarefree, and let <m>K=\Q(\sqrt{d})</m>. For any <m>\alpha=q_1+q_2\sqrt{d}\in K</m>, we define its <term>conjugate</term> <m>\overline{\alpha}</m> and <term>norm</term> <m>N_K(\alpha)</m> as follows: 
    <md>
        <mrow>\overline{\alpha} \amp =q_1-q_2\sqrt{d}\amp N_K(\alpha)\amp=\alpha\overline{\alpha}=q_1^2-q_2^2\sqrt{d}</mrow>
    </md>.
    We call the resulting function <m>N_K\colon K\rightarrow \Q</m> the <term>norm function</term> of <m>K</m> over <m>\Q</m>. 
    </p>
    </statement>
    </definition>
    
    <warning>
    <p>
        It is important not to conflate the general conjugate and norm operations of a quadratic field with <em>complex conjugation</em> and the <em>Gaussian norm</em> function. 
    </p>
    <p>
        Take quadratic field <m>K=\Q(\sqrt{2})</m>, for example. Given any <m>\alpha=q_1+q_2\sqrt{2}\in K</m>, we have 
        <md>
            <mrow>\overline{\alpha} \amp = q_1-q_2\sqrt{2} \amp N_K(\alpha)=q_1^2-2q_2^2</mrow>
        </md>.
        There operations are clearly different than complex conjugation and the Gaussian norm. For instance we have <m>\overline{3+2\sqrt{2}}=3-2\sqrt{2}</m>, whereas the complex conjugate of <m>3+2\sqrt{2}</m> is itself (since it is real)! Furthermore, note that <m>N_K</m> can assume negative values (<m>N_K(2+3\sqrt{2})=4-18=-14</m>), whereas the Gaussian norm is a nonnegative function. 
    </p>
    <p>
        That said, in the case where <m>K=\Q(\sqrt{d})</m> is imaginary (<ie/>, <m>d&lt; 0</m>), then the quadratic conjugate and norm operations are in fact identical to complex conjugation and modulus squared. 
    </p>
    </warning>
    <proposition xml:id="prop_quad_norm">
        <title>Quadratic conjugates and norms</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>d\in \Z-\{0,1\}</m> be a squarefree integer, and let <m>K=\Q(\sqrt{d})</m>. As usual, given <m>\alpha=q_1+q_2\sqrt{d}</m>, we define <m>\overline{\alpha}=q_1-q_2\sqrt{d}</m>. 
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                          For all <m>\alpha,\beta\in K</m>, we have 
                <md number="yes">
                    <mrow>\overline{\alpha\beta} \amp =\overline{\alpha}\, \overline{\beta}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\overline{\alpha+\beta} \amp = \overline{\alpha}+\overline{\beta} </mrow>
                    <mrow>N_K(\alpha\beta) \amp =N_K(\alpha)N_K(\beta)</mrow>
                </md>. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Given <m>\alpha\in K</m>, we have 
                            <md number="yes">
                                <mrow>\alpha\in \Q \amp \iff \overline{\alpha}=\alpha</mrow>
                                <mrow>N_K(\alpha)=0\amp \iff \alpha=0 </mrow>
                            </md>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                
            </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            These are simple algebraic arguments left to the reader. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Observe first that <m>\Q=\{\alpha\in \Q(\sqrt{d})\mid \alpha=q+0\sqrt{d}\}</m>. Now given <m>\alpha=q_1+q_2\sqrt{d}</m>, we have 
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\alpha=\overline{\alpha} \amp \iff q_1+q_2\sqrt{d}=q_1-q_2\sqrt{d}</mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp \iff q_1=q_1 \text{ and } q_2=-q_2 \amp (<xref ref="prop_quad_ext_equality" text="global"/>)</mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp \iff q_2=0</mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp \iff \alpha\in \Q</mrow>
                            </md>.
                            For the second part, given <m>\alpha=q_1+q_2\sqrt{d}</m>,  we have 
                            <md number="yes">   
                                <mrow>N_K(\alpha)=0  \amp \iff  q_1^2-q_2^2d=0 </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp \iff  q_1^2=q_2^2d</mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp \iff q_1=q_2=0 \amp (<xref ref="prop_quad_ext_equality" text="global"/>)</mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp \iff \alpha=0</mrow>
                            </md>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </proof>
    </proposition>
    <theorem xml:id="th_quad_ext_field">
    <title>Quadratic extensions of <m>\Q</m> are fields</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Let <m>d\in \Z-\{0,1\}</m> be a squarefree integer, and let <m>K=\Q(\sqrt{d})</m>. 
    <ol>
        <li>
            <p>
                <m>K</m> is a subring of <m>\C</m>. 
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                Every nonzero element of <m>K</m> has a multiplicative inverse: <ie/>, <m>K</m> is a <em>field</em>. More explicitly, given nonzero <m>\alpha=q_1+q_2\sqrt{d}\in K</m>, we have 
                <md number="yes">
                    <mrow>\alpha^{-1} \amp =\frac{q_1}{q_1^2-q_2^2d}-\frac{q_2}{q_1^2-q_2^2d}=\frac{\overline{\alpha}}{N_K(\alpha)}</mrow>
                </md>.

            </p>
        </li>
    </ol>
    </p>
    </statement>
    <proof>
    <p>
        <ol>
            <li>
                <p>
                    We need only show that <m>K</m> contains <m>0</m> and <m>1</m>, and is closed under addition, additive inverses (<m>-\alpha</m>), and multiplication. These are simple algebraic arguments left to the reader. 
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    This is an immediate consequence of the fact that <m>\alpha\ne 0</m> implies <m>N_K(\alpha)\ne 0</m> and the following algebra: 
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\alpha\cdot \frac{\alpha}{N_K(\alpha)} \amp = \frac{\alpha\overline{\alpha}}{N_K(\alpha)}</mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp =\frac{N_K(\alpha)}{N_K(\alpha)}</mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp = 1</mrow>
                    </md>.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </p>
    </proof>
    </theorem>
    
</subsection>
<subsection xml:id="ss_ring_of_integers">
<title>Ring of integers</title>
<definition xml:id="d_monic">
<title>Monic polynomial</title>
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>R</m> be a ring. A polynomial <m>f\in R[x]</m> is <term>monic</term> if its leading coefficient is 1: <ie/>, if <m>f(x)=\anmonic</m>, with <m>a_i\in R</m> for all <m>0\leq i\leq n-1</m>. 
</p>
</statement>
</definition>

<definition xml:id="d_alg_integers">
<title>Algebraic integers of <m>\C</m></title>
<statement>
<p>
A complex number <m>\alpha\in \C</m> is an <term>algebraic integer</term> if there is a monic polynomial <m>f\in \Z[x]</m> such that <m>f(\alpha)=0</m>. 
</p>
</statement>
</definition>
<remark>
<title>Algebraic versus algebraic integer</title>
<p>
Recall that an element <m>\alpha\in \Q</m> is <em>algebraic</em> if there is a polynomial <m>f\in \Q[x]</m> such that <m>f(\alpha)=0</m>. The condition for being an algebraic integer is stricter on two counts: we must be able to find a polynomial not just with rational coefficients, but integer ones; furthermore, the polynomial must be monic.
</p>
<p>
    Note in this regard that any algebraic element <m>\alpha\in \C</m> will satisfy a polynomial with integer coefficients, just by clearing denominators in the polynomial <m>f\in \Q[x]</m> satisfying <m>f(\alpha)=0</m>. For example, the element <m>\alpha=\frac{\sqrt{2}}{3}</m> satisfies the monic rational polynomial <m>f(x)=x^2-2/9</m> and the integer polynomial <m>g(x)=9x^2-2</m>. However, we will be able to show that <m>\alpha</m> does <em>not</em> satisfy a <em>monic</em> integer polynomial. 
</p>
</remark>
<p>
    We will primarily be interested in the algebraic integers lying within one of our quadratic fields <m>\Q(\sqrt{d})</m>. Before we get there, we assemble some general results about algebraic integers. 
</p>
<theorem xml:id="th_alg_int_ring">
<title>Algebraic integers form a ring</title>
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>\mathcal{O}</m> be the set of all algebraic integers in <m>\C</m>: <ie/>, 
<md>\mathcal{O}=\{\alpha\in \C\mid f(\alpha)=0 \text{ for some monic } f\in \Z[x]\}</md>.
<ol>
    <li>
        <p>
            <m>\mathcal{O}\cap \Q=\Z</m>. In other words, all integers are algebraic integers, and furthermore, the set of rational numbers that are algebraic integers is precisely <m>\Z</m>. 
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            <m>\mathcal{O}</m> is closed under addition and multiplication: <ie/>, we have 
            <md>
                <mrow>\alpha,\beta\in \mathcal{O} \amp \implies \alpha+\beta, \alpha\beta\in \mathcal{O}</mrow>
            </md>.
        </p>
    </li>
</ol>
As a result, <m>\mathcal{O}</m> is a subring of <m>\C</m>. 
</p>
</statement>
<proof>
<p>
    <ol>
        <li>
            <p>
                If <m>n\in \Z</m>, then <m>f(n)=0</m> for the monic integer polynomial <m>f(x)=x-n</m>. Thus <m>\Z\subseteq \mathcal{O}\cap \Q</m>. 
            </p>
            <p>
                Conversely, suppose <m>q\in \mathcal{O}\cap \Q</m>. Let <m>f(x)=\anmonic</m> be a monic polynomial satisfying <m>f(q)=0</m>. Writing <m>q=r/s</m> with <m>\gcd(r,s)=1</m> and clearing denominators in the equation <m>f(r/s)=0</m>, we see that 
                <md>
                    r^n+a_{n-1}r^{n-1}s+\cdots +a_1rs^{n-1}+a_0s^n=0
                </md>.
                Since all constants above are integers, we see that <m>s\mid r^n</m>, a contradiction since <m>\gcd(r,s)=1</m>.
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                As intuitive as this property might sound, we resort to a little linear algebra trickery to prove it. Namely, we first prove the following sufficient condition for an element <m>\alpha\in \C</m> to be an algebraic integer: if there is a set <m>\{\theta_1,\theta_2,\dots, \theta_k\}</m> of complex numbers, not all zero, such that for all <m>1\leq j\leq k</m> we have 
                <md>
                    \alpha\theta_j=\sum_{i=1}^kb_{ij}\theta_i
                </md>
                for some integer constants <m>b_{ij}\in \Z</m>, then <m>\alpha</m> is an algebraic integer.
            </p>
            <p>
                Before proving this claim, let's see why it yields the desired result. Suppose that <m>\alpha</m> and <m>\beta</m> are algebraic integers satisfying <m>f(\alpha)=0</m> and <m>g(\beta)=0</m>, where <m>f(x)=\anmonic</m> and <m>g(x)=x^m+b_{m-1}x^{m-1}+\cdots +b_1x+b_0</m> are monic integer polynomials. Since 
                <md>
                    <mrow>\alpha^n \amp =-\sum_{i=0}^{n-1}a_i\alpha^{i}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\beta^m \amp = -\sum_{i=0}^{m-1}b_i\beta^{i}</mrow>
                </md>,
                it follows that the set 
                <md>
                    X=\{\alpha^{i}\beta^{j}\mid 0\leq i\leq n-1, 0\leq j\leq m-1\}
                </md>
                satisfies the condition above for <m>\alpha</m> and <m>\beta</m>. Indeed, we have 
                <md>
                    <mrow>\alpha (\alpha^i\beta^j) \amp = \begin{cases}
                    \alpha^{i+1}\beta^j\amp  \text{if } 0\leq i\leq n-2\\
                    -\sum_{\ell=0}^{n-1}a_{\ell}\alpha^\ell \beta^j\amp  \text{if } i=n-1
                    \end{cases}</mrow>
                     <mrow>\beta (\alpha^i\beta^j) \amp = \begin{cases}
                    \alpha^{i}\beta^{j+1}\amp  \text{if } 0\leq j\leq m-2\\
                    -\sum_{\ell=0}^{m-1}b_{\ell}\alpha^i \beta^\ell \amp  \text{if } j=m-1
                    \end{cases}</mrow>
                </md>.
                But then it follows easily that <m>\alpha+\beta</m> and <m>\alpha\beta</m> also satisfy the claims condition with respect to <m>X</m>, showing that these elements are also algebraic integers. 
            </p>
        </li>
    </ol>
</p>
</proof>
</theorem>
<p>
    With these generalities out of the way, we can now define the ring of integers of a quadratic field <m>\Q(\sqrt{d})</m>. 
</p>
<definition xml:id="d_quad_ring_integers">
<title>Quadratic ring of integers</title>
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>d\in \Z-\{0,1\}</m> be squarefree, and let <m>K=\Q(\sqrt{d})</m>. The <term>ring of integers</term> of <m>K</m>, denoted <m>\mathcal{O}_K</m> is the set of all elements of <m>K</m> that are algebraic integers: <ie/>, 
<md number="yes">
    <mrow>\mathcal{O}_K \amp = \{\alpha\in K\mid f(\alpha)=0 \text{ for some monic } f\in \Z[x]\}</mrow>
</md>.
We call <m>\mathcal{O}_K</m> a <term>quadratic ring of integers</term>. 
</p>
</statement>
</definition>
<theorem xml:id="th_quad_ring_integers">
<title>Quadratic ring of integers</title>
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>d\in \Z-\{0,1\}</m> be a squarefree integer, and let <m>K=\Q(\sqrt{d})</m>. 
<ol>
    <li>
        <p>
            <m>\mathcal{O}_K</m> is a subring of <m>\C</m>. 
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            Given <m>\alpha\in K</m>, we have <m>\alpha\in \mathcal{O}_K</m> if and only if <m>\alpha+\overline{\alpha}\in \Z</m> and <m>\alpha\overline{\alpha}\in \Z</m>. 
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            We have 
            <md number="yes">
                <mrow xml:id="eq_quad_ring_int">\mathcal{O}_K \amp =\begin{cases}
                \Z[\sqrt{d}]=\{a+b\sqrt{d}\mid a,b\in \Z\} \amp \text{if } d\equiv 2,3\pmod 4\\
                \Z[\omega]=\{a+b\omega\mid a,b\in \Z\}, \text{ where } \omega=\tfrac{1}{2}+\tfrac{\sqrt{d}}{2} \amp \text{if } d\equiv 1\pmod 4
                \end{cases}</mrow>
            </md>.
        </p>
    </li>
</ol>
</p>
</statement>
<proof>
<p>
    <ol>
        <li>
            <p>
                This follows easily from the fact the set of algebraic integers is closed under addition and multiplication, as is <m>K</m>. 
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                Note that <m>\alpha</m> is a root of the monic polynomial 
                <md>
                    <mrow>f(x) \amp =(x-\alpha)(x-\overline{\alpha})=x^2-(\alpha+\overline{\alpha})x+\alpha\overline{\alpha}</mrow>
                </md>.
                If <m>\alpha+\overline{\alpha}\in \Z</m> and <m>\alpha\overline{\alpha}\in \Z</m>, then <m>f\in \Z[x]</m> and thus <m>\alpha\in \mathcal{O}_K</m>. 
            </p>
            <p>
                Conversely, assume <m>\alpha\in\mathcal{O}_K</m>, and suppose <m>f(\alpha)=0</m> for the polynomial <m>f(x)=\anmonic\in \Z</m>. Since <m>\overline{a_i}=a_i</m> for all <m>0\leq i\leq n-1</m>, we see that 
                <md>
                    <mrow>0 \amp =\overline{f(\alpha)}</mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp =\overline{a_n}\overline{\alpha}^n+\overline{a_{n-1}}\overline{\alpha}^{n-1}+\cdots +\overline{a_1}\alpha+\overline{a_0}</mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = a_n\overline{\alpha}^n+a_{n-1}\overline{\alpha}^{n-1}+\cdots +a_1\alpha+a_0</mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = f(\overline{\alpha})</mrow>
                </md>.
                Thus <m>\overline{\alpha}</m> is also a root of <m>f</m>, showing tha that <m>\overline{\alpha}\in \mathcal{O}_K</m>. It follows that <m>\alpha+\overline{\alpha}</m> and <m>\alpha\overline{\alpha}</m> are elements of <m>\mathcal{O}_K</m>. Lastly, since 
                <md>
                    <mrow>\overline{\alpha+\overline{\alpha}} \amp =\overline{\alpha}+\alpha</mrow>
                    <mrow>\overline{\alpha\overline{\alpha}} \amp = \overline{\alpha}\alpha</mrow>
                </md>,
                we see that <m>\alpha+\overline{\alpha},\alpha\overline{\alpha}\in \Q</m>. From (1) of <xref ref="th_alg_int_ring"/>, we conclude that <m>\alpha+\overline{\alpha},\alpha\overline{\alpha}\in \Z</m>.
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                Using the condition from (2), it is easy to see that elements of the rings on the right side of the equality <xref ref="eq_quad_ring_int"/> are elements of <m>\mathcal{O}_K</m>. It remains to show that the reverse inclusion. 
            </p>
            <p>
                Assume <m>\alpha=q_1+q_2\sqrt{d}\in \mathcal{O}_K</m>. From (2) it follows that <m>\alpha+\overline{\alpha},\alpha\overline{\alpha}\in \Z</m>. We have 
                <md>
                    <mrow>\alpha+\overline{\alpha} \amp =2q_1</mrow>
                    <mrow>\alpha\overline{\alpha} \amp =q_1^2-q_2^2d</mrow>
                </md>.
                Since <m>2q_1\in \Z</m>, we have <m>q_1=m/2</m> for some integer <m>m</m>. 
            </p>
            <p>
                Assume first that <m>m</m> is even, so that <m>q_1\in \Z</m>. It follows that <m>q_2^2d=a\in \Z</m>. Using the fact that <m>d</m> is square free, we can show that <m>q_2\in \Z</m> in this case. Indeed, writing <m>q_2=r/s</m> with <m>\gcd(r,s)=1</m>, we have <m>r^2d=s^2a</m>. If <m>s</m> had a prime divisor <m>p</m>, <m>p^2\mid s^2a</m>, and since <m>\gcd(r,s)=1</m>, we'd have <m>p^2\mid d</m>. Thus when <m>q_1\in \Z</m> is an integer, <m>q_2\in \Z</m>, and we have <m>\alpha\in \Z[\sqrt{d}]\subseteq \Z[\omega]</m>. 
            </p>
            <p>
                Now assume <m>q_1=m/2</m> with <m>m</m> odd. Since 
                <md>
                    \frac{m^2}{4}-q_2^2d\in \Z
                </md>,
                we have <m>4q_2^2=(2q_2)^2d\in \Z</m>. The same argument above implies that <m>2q_2\in \Z</m>, and thus <m>q_2=n/2</m> for some integer <m>n\in \Z</m>. But then we have 
                <md>
                    \frac{m^2}{4}-\frac{n^2}{4}d\in \Z
                </md>,
                in which case <m>m^2-n^2d\equiv 1-n^2d 0\pmod 4</m>. But this can happen if and only if <m>n^2d\equiv 1\pmod 4</m>. This in turn forces <m>n</m> and <m>d</m> to both be odd, in which case <m>n^2d\equiv 1d\equiv d\equiv 1\pmod 4</m>. Thus in this case we must have <m>d\equiv 1\pmod 4</m>, and we have 
                <md>
                    <mrow>\alpha \amp = q_1+q_2\sqrt{d}</mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \frac{m}{2}+\frac{n}{2}\sqrt{d}</mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \frac{m-n}{2}+n\left(\frac{1}{2}+\sqrt{d}{2}\right)</mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp =m'+n\omega</mrow>
                </md>,
                where <m>m',n\in \Z</m> since <m>m-n</m> is even. 
            </p>
        </li>
    </ol>
</p>
</proof>
</theorem>
<p>
    As with <m>\Z[i]</m>, the multiplicative units of <m>\mathcal{O}_K</m> play an important role in our analysis of these rings. We will say much more about these units in the next section. For now we content ourselves with a definition and a first elementary proposition. 
</p>
<definition xml:id="d_quad_ring_units">
<title>Units of <m>\mathcal{O}_K</m></title>
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>d\in \Z-\{0,1\}</m> be squarefree, and let <m>K=\Q(\sqrt{d})</m>. An element <m>\alpha \in \mathcal{O}_K</m> is a <term>unit</term> (or <term>invertible</term>) if there is an element <m>\beta\in \mathcal{O}_K</m> such that <m>\alpha\beta=1</m>. The <term>group of units</term> of <m>\mathcal{O}_K</m> is the set <m>\mathcal{O}_K^*</m> of all units: <ie/>, 
<md>
    \mathcal{O}_K^*=\{\alpha\in \mathcal{O}_K\mid \alpha\beta=1 \text{ for some } \beta\in \mathcal{O}_K^*\}
</md>.
</p>
</statement>
</definition>
<proposition xml:id="prop_quad_ring_units">
    <title>Units of <m>\mathcal{O}_K</m></title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Let <m>d\in \Z-\{0,1\}</m> be squarefree, and let <m>K=\Q(\sqrt{d})</m>. An element <m>\alpha\in \mathcal{O}_K</m> if and only if <m>N_K(\alpha)=\pm 1</m>. In other words
            <md>
                \mathcal{O}_K=\{\alpha\in \mathcal{O}_K\mid N_K(\alpha)=\pm 1\}
            </md>.
        </p>
    </statement>
    <proof>
        <p>
            We prove both implications separately. 
        </p>
        <p>
            If <m>\alpha\in \mathcal{O}_K^*</m>, then there is an element <m>\beta\in \mathcal{O}_K</m> such that <m>\alpha\beta=1</m>. Taking norms, we conclude that <m>N_K(\alpha)N_K(\beta)=1</m>. Since <m>N_K(\alpha)</m> and <m>N_K(\beta)</m> are both integers by <xref ref="th_quad_ring_integers"/>, and since the only divisors of <m>1</m> are <m>\pm 1</m>, we conclude that <m>N_K(\alpha)\in \{-1,1\}</m>. 
        </p>
        <p>
            Conversely, if <m>N_K(\alpha)=\alpha\overline{\alpha}=\pm 1</m>, then we see that <m>\alpha(\pm \overline{\alpha}}=1</m> and thus <m>\pm \overline{\alpha}</m> is an inverse of <m>\alpha</m> in <m>\C</m>. Since <m>\alpha\in \mathcal{O}_K</m> if and only if <m>\overline{\alpha}\in \mathcal{O}_K</m>, we see that <m>\pm \overline{\alpha}\in \mathcal{O}_K</m>, showing that <m>\alpha\in \mathcal{O}_K^*</m>. 
        </p>
    </proof>
</proposition>
<p>
    When analyzing <m>\Z[i]</m> we made heavy use of the fact that the Gaussian norm function <m>N\colon \Z[i]\rightarrow \Z</m> satisfied a division algorithm property. Interestingly, the same cannot be said of a general norm function <m>N_K</m> for the ring of integers <m>\mathcal{O}_K</m>. Accordingly, we give a name to those special rings for which this is true. 
</p>
<definition xml:id="d_norm_euclidean">
<title>Norm-Euclidean</title>
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>d\in \Z-\{0,1\}</m> be squarefree, and let <m>K=\Q(\sqrt{d})</m>. The norm <m>N_K</m> <term>satisfies the division algorithm</term> if given <m>\alpha,\beta\in \mathcal{O}_K</m> with <m>\beta\ne 0</m>, there exist <m>\gamma,\delta\in \mathcal{O}_K</m> satisfying the following conditions. 
<ol>
    <li>
        <p>
            <m>\alpha=\gamma\beta+\delta</m>.
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            <m>0\leq \abs{N_K(\delta)}\leq \abs{N_K(\beta)}</m>.
        </p>
    </li>
</ol>
We also say that <m>\mathcal{O}_K</m> is <term>norm-Euclidean</term> in this case. 
</p>
</statement>
</definition>
<p>
    The importance of a quadratic ring of integer <m>\mathcal{O}_K</m> being norm-Euclidean is that we can perform a version of the Euclidean algorithm (<xref ref="th_euc_alg"/>) using <m>\abs{N_K}</m> to compute GCDs of elements <m>\alpha, \beta\in \mathcal{O}_K</m>, and moreover, express a GCD in the form <m>\gamma\alpha+\delta\beta</m> as in Bezout's theorem. As we saw in the discussion of <m>\Z[i]</m>, that fact then leads to a cascade of useful properties we used to classify the prime elements of <m>\Z[i]</m>. As a result, these same properties hold for a norm-Euclidean <m>\mathcal{O}_K</m>.
</p>
<theorem xml:id="th_norm_euc">
<title>Norm-Euclidean rings of integers</title>
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>d\in \Z-\{0,1\}</m> be squarefree, and let <m>K=\Q(\sqrt{d})</m>. If <m>\mathcal{O}_K</m> is norm-Euclidean then it enjoys the following properties. 
<ol>
    <li>
        <p>
            Let <m>\alpha,\beta\in \mathcal{O}_K</m> and assume <m>\alpha\ne 0</m> or <m>\beta\ne 0</m>. There is a GCD <m>\delta</m> of <m>\alpha</m> and <m>\beta</m>, and we have <m>\delta=\gamma \alpha+\epsilon \beta</m> for some <m>\gamma, \epsilon\in \mathcal{O}_K</m>. 
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            An element <m>\pi\in \mathcal{O}_K</m> is prime if and only if it is irreducible. 
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            If <m>\alpha\in \mathcal{O}_K</m> is a nonzero non-unit, then it has a factorization <m>\alpha=\prod_{i=1}^r\pi_i</m> where <m>\pi_i</m> is irreducible for all <m>1\leq i\leq r</m>, and this factorization is unique in the sense of <xref ref="th_unique_factorization_gauss"/>.
        </p>
    </li>
</ol>
</p>
</statement>
<proof>
<p>
    The proofs of these statements can be adapted immediately from the proofs of the corresponding results for <m>\Z[i]</m>, all of which build on the fact that the norm satisfies the division algorithm. 
</p>
</proof>
</theorem>
<p>
    Without making things official here, a ring that satisfies the factorization property described in (4) of <xref ref="th_norm_euc"/> is called a <em>unique factorization domain</em>, or <em>UFD</em> for short. Thus, the theorem tells us that if a quadratic ring of integers <m>\mathcal{O}_K</m> is norm-equivalent, then it is a UFD. Interestingly, although not all of these rings are UFDs, they all do admit irreducible factorizations. Note that we are careful to say <em>irreducible</em> factorizations in this context, as we cannot assume that prime and irreducible are equivalent. 
</p>
<theorem xml:id="th_quad_ring_irr_fact">
<title>Irreducible factorizations in quadratic rings of integers</title>
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>d\in \Z-\{0,1\}</m> be a squarefree, let <m>K=\Q(\sqrt{d})</m>, and let <m>\alpha</m> be a nonzero non-unit of <m>\mathcal{O}_K</m>. There are irreducible elements <m>\pi_i\in \mathcal{O}_K</m>, <m>1\leq i\leq r</m> such that <m>\alpha=\prod_{i=1}^r\pi_i</m>.  
</p>
</statement>
<proof>
    
<p>
    We will prove by by strong induction on <m>\abs{N_K(\alpha)}</m> that every element <m>\alpha\in \mathcal{O}_K</m> can be factored into irreducibles. 
</p>
<p>
    First observe that <m>\abs{N(\sqrt{d})}=\abs{d}&gt; 1</m>, and thus that the set <m>X=\{\abs{N_K(\alpha)}\mid \alpha\in \mathcal{O}_K\}-\{1\}</m> is nonempty. Let <m>n_0</m> be the least element of <m>X</m>. This is our base case for the induction argument. Assume <m>\abs{N_K(\alpha)}=n_0</m>. If <m>\alpha=\beta\gamma</m>, then 
    <md>
        n_0=\abs{N_K(\alpha)}=\abs{N_K(\beta\gamma)}=\abs{N_K(\beta)}\abs{N_K(\gamma)}
    </md>,
    and thus <m>1\leq \abs{N_K(\beta)},\abs{N_K(\gamma)}\leq n_0</m>. Since <m>n_0</m> is the minimal absolute norm of elements of <m>\mathcal{O}_K</m>, it follows that <m>\{\abs{N_K(\beta)},\abs{N_K(\gamma)}\}=\{1,n_0\}</m>. But then <m>\beta</m> or <m>\gamma</m> is a unit, by <xref ref="prop_quad_ring_units"/>. This proves <m>\alpha</m> is irreducible. 
</p>
<p>
    Now assume the statement is true for all <m>\beta\in \mathcal{O}_K</m> with <m>n_0\leq \abs{N_K(\beta)}&lt; n</m>, and assume <m>\abs{N_K(\alpha)}=n</m>. If <m>\alpha</m> is irreducible, then we are done. Otherwise, we can write <m>\alpha=\beta\gamma</m>, where <m>\beta</m> and <m>\gamma</m> are non-units. It follows that 
    <md>
        n_0\leq  \abs{N_K(\beta)}, \abs{N_K(\gamma)}&lt; n
    </md>,
    whence the induction hypothesis applies. We conclude that <m>\gamma</m> and <m>\beta</m> have irreducible factorizations. Since <m>\alpha=\beta\gamma</m>, the product of these two irreducible factorizations is an irreducible factorization of <m>\alpha</m>.
</p>
</proof>
</theorem>
<example xml:id="eg_quad_ring_UFD">
<title><m>\Z[\sqrt{-5}]</m> is not a UFD</title>
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>K=\Q(\sqrt{5}i)</m>and consider <m>\mathcal{O}_K=\Z[\sqrt{-5}]=\Z[\sqrt{5}i]</m>. (Note that <m>-5\equiv 3\pmod 4</m>.)
<ol>
    <li>
        <p>
            Compute <m>\mathcal{O}_K^*</m>. 
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            Show that <m>2</m>, <m>3</m>, <m>1+\sqrt{5}i</m> and <m>1-\sqrt{5}i</m> are pairwise non-associate irreducible elements of <m>\Z[\sqrt{5}i]</m>. 
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
       <p>
        Show that <m>\Z[\sqrt{5}i]</m> is not a UFD. 
       </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            Show that none of the irreducible elements <m>2</m>, <m>3</m>, <m>1+\sqrt{5}i</m>, <m>1-\sqrt{5}i</m> are prime. Thus prime is not equivalent to irreducible in <m>\Z[\sqrt{5}i]</m>. 
        </p>
    </li>
</ol>
</p>
</statement>
<solution>
    <p>
        <ol>
            <li>
                <p>
                    An element <m>\alpha=a+b\sqrt{5}i</m> is a unit if and only if <m>N_K(\alpha)=a^2+5b^2=1</m>. It follows easily that the only units of <m>\mathcal{O}_K</m> are <m>1</m> and <m>-1</m>. 
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Since <m>\mathcal{O}_K=\{1,-1\}</m>, it follows easily that the listed elements are pairwise non-associate. 
                </p>
                <p>
                    We prove <m>2</m> is irreducible; the same argument can be used for the remaining elements. If <m>2=\alpha\beta</m> for <m>\alpha,\beta\in \Z[\sqrt{5}i]</m>, then taking norms, we see that <m>4=N_K(\alpha)N_K(\beta)</m>. It is easy to see that there are no elements of <m>\Z[\sqrt{5}i]</m> with norm equal to <m>2</m> (or <m>3</m>). Thus we must have <m>\{N_K(\alpha),N_K(\beta)\}=\{1, 4\}</m>, showing that <m>\alpha</m> or <m>\beta</m> is a unit, and hence <m>2</m> is irreducible.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                   The factorizations <m>6=2\cdot 3</m> and <m>6=(1+\sqrt{5}i)(1-\sqrt{5}i)</m> give us two irreducible factorizations of 6 consisting of non-associate irreducibles. Thus irreducible factorization is not unique in <m>\mathcal{O}_K</m>, showing that it is not a UFD. 
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    The two factorizations above also show us that <m>2</m>, <m>3</m>, <m>1+\sqrt{5}i</m>, and <m>1-\sqrt{5}i</m> are not prime. For example, we have <m>2\mid 6=(1+\sqrt{5}i)(1-\sqrt{5}i)</m>, but <m>2\nmid(1+\sqrt{5}i)</m> and <m>2\nmid (1-\sqrt{5}i)</m>. 
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </p>
</solution>
</example>

</subsection>

</section>